[11.390654, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[?7l\u001b[0m\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\u001b[0m \u001b[0m\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\r\r\n\u001b[0m \b\u001b[44A\u001b[46C\u001b[?7h\u001b[0m\u001b[?12l\u001b[?25h"]
[13.645081, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[?7l\u001b[46D\u001b[0m\u001b[J\u001b[0;1m[D]iscuss  [E]xecute  [Q]uick  (enter=quick):\u001b[45D\u001b[0m\r\r\n\u001b[J\u001b[?7h\u001b[0m\u001b[?12l\u001b[?25h\u001b[?2004l"]
[22.190305, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1m\u001b[36m◆ scout\u001b[0m \u001b[2m(Researcher)\u001b[0m\r\nKey difference:\r\n\r\n- `asyncio.gather` = “run these coroutines and give me their **results in order**, or raise if one fails.”\r\n- `asyncio.wait` = “run these coroutines and give me **which ones are done/pending**, I’ll handle results/errors myself.”\r\n\r\nMore concretely:\r\n\r\n### `asyncio.gather(*aws, return_exceptions=False)`\r\n\r\n- Accepts awaitables (coroutines, Tasks, Futures).\r\n- Schedules them and waits for **all** to finish.\r\n- Returns a list/tuple of results in **the same order** as arguments.\r\n- If any raises:\r\n  - By default: `gather` raises the first exception and cancels the rest.\r\n  - With `return_exceptions=True`: exceptions are returned as items instead of raised.\r\n- Great when you:\r\n  - Want “fire many, wait for all, get all results.”\r\n  - Don’t care about partial completion/timeouts.\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n```python\r\nresults = await asyncio.gather(coro1(), coro2(), coro3())\r\n# results[0] corresponds to coro1(), etc.\r\n```\r\n\r\n### `asyncio.wait(aws, *, timeout=None, return_when=ALL_COMPLETED)`\r\n\r\n- Accepts an **iterable** of awaitables.\r\n- Returns two sets: `(done, pending)` of **Tasks**.\r\n- Does **not** gather results for you; you must `task.result()` yourself.\r\n- `return_when` controls when it returns:\r\n  - `ALL_COMPLETED` (default)\r\n  - `FIRST_COMPLETED`\r\n  - `FIRST_EXCEPTION`\r\n- Useful when you:\r\n  - Need to handle tasks as they complete (streaming results).\r\n  - Want to implement timeouts and cancel remaining tasks.\r\n  - Need fine-grained control over error handling/cancellation.\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n```python\r\ndone, pending = await asyncio.wait(\r\n    [coro1(), coro2(), coro3()],\r\n    return_when=asyncio.FIRST_COMPLETED\r\n)\r\nfor task in done:\r\n    print(task.result())\r\nfor task in pending:\r\n    task.cancel()\r\n```\r\n\r\nActionable guidance:\r\n- Use `gather` for simple “parallel await” and ordered results.\r\n- Use `wait` when you care about completion timing, cancellation, or partial results.\r\n\r\nWhat’s your use case: do you mainly need ordered results from all tasks, or do you need to react as tasks finish/timeout?\r\n\r\n"]
[22.191448, "o", "\u001b[6n"]
